trans:
Important! Different forms of bilirubin have varying toxicity for tissues. Indirect bilirubin is highly toxic to nervous tissues. By binding with other proteins, it transitions into the conjugated form and is excreted from the body through feces.
Causes and Symptoms
The reasons for the increase in pigment levels are different:
Intensive destruction of erythrocytes;
problems with bile flow to the duodenum;
consequences of taking medications;
worm infestations;
lack of vitamin B12 in the body.
Frequent symptoms:
dizziness and migraines;
rapid fatigue;
attacks of nausea, vomiting, itching;
yellowing of mucous membranes and sclera of the eyes;
dark urine;
elevated temperature.
The accumulation of bilirubin can lead to jaundice and exacerbate chronic diseases. Elevated levels in the blood can cause nervous disorders. General recommendations (what should not be eaten and done):
More often is better. Increasing meals to 6 times a day will help normalize the level of the substance in the blood.
With elevated bilirubin and cholesterol, it is not recommended to consume fried and smoked dishes. It is better to choose steaming, baking, or boiled food.
The daily salt intake should not exceed 10 grams.
Carbohydrates should predominate in the diet. The norm is up to 500 grams per day.
